diate present to the imagined past, from the barrio to the socialist state. Wirtz analyzes a variety of performances and the ways they construct Cuban racial and historical imaginations. She offers a sophisticated view of performance as enacting diverse revolutionary ideals, religious notions, and racial identity politics, and she outlines how these concepts play out in the ongoing institutionalization of folklore as an official, even state-sponsored, category. Employing Bakhtin’s concept of “chronotopes”—the semiotic construction of space-time—she examines the roles of voice, temporality, embodiment, imagery, and memory in the racializing process. The result is a deftly balanced study that marries racial studies, performance studies, anthropology, and semiotics to explore the nature of race as a cultural sign, one that is always in process, always shifting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBlack peoplexRace identityzCuba. 0aBlack peoplezCubaxSocial conditions. 0aBlack peoplezCubaxSocial life and customs. 0aBlacksxRace identityxCuba. 0aBlacksxRace identityzCuba. 0aBlacksxSocial conditionsxCuba. 0aBlacksxSocial life and customsxCuba. 0aBlackszCubaxSocial conditions. 0aBlackszCubaxSocial life and customs. 0aFolklorexHistoryxCuba. 0aFolklorezCubaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aperformance, image, voice, spectacle, race, racism, racist, history, historical, academic, scholarly, research, cuban, african, racial, identity, visitor, tourist, popular, music, folklore, dance, culture, cultural, santeria, dolls, gifts, plantation, colonial, colonialism, decolonized, blackness, black experience, heritage, socialist, imagination, revolutionary, politics, political.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-20